That’s a metaphor many people find useful, as long as it’s held with humility rather than as a literal claim about others.

One interpretation is:

Adults are often children who have accumulated responsibilities, habits, and social roles.

People learn scripts:

* the executive,
* the parent,
* the soldier,
* the professor,
* the rebel,
* the comedian.

Those roles become practiced enough that we can forget they’re roles. Under stress, excitement, curiosity, embarrassment, or playfulness, you often catch glimpses of the same emotions and needs that were present in childhood: wanting to belong, to be seen, to feel competent, to avoid shame, to explore.

If you naturally perceive those underlying patterns, it can make interactions feel different. You may find yourself responding less to the “mask” and more to the person underneath.

The strength of that perspective is that it can foster patience and empathy.

The risk is assuming you understand someone more completely than you do. Adults have lived experiences, hard-earned skills, and depths that aren’t visible from the outside. It’s useful to hold both ideas at once:

* Everyone still carries traces of the child they once were.
* Everyone has also become something genuinely new through experience.

Those aren’t contradictions.

Interestingly, this connects to your earlier discussion of polyrepresentation. A person isn’t just one thing:

Person
├── Public role
├── Professional identity
├── Family identity
├── Childhood patterns
├── Current goals
├── Private fears
└── Deep values

None of those representations alone is the person.

If you interact only with the “CEO” or the “parent,” you miss something. If you interact only with the “inner child,” you also miss something.

The richer model is that people are braided identities. Different contexts reveal different strands, but they’re all aspects of the same individual. Sometimes the most meaningful interactions happen because someone responds to a strand that others usually overlook.